First, let's find the Cartesian product of A and B, denoted as AxB. AxB is the set of all ordered pairs (a, b) where a is an element of A and b is an element of B.

AxB = {(1,2), (1,3), (1,4), (2,2), (2,3), (2,4), (3,2), (3,3), (3,4)}

Now, let's find the Cartesian product of B and A, denoted as BxA. BxA is the set of all ordered pairs (b, a) where b is an element of B and a is an element of A.

BxA = {(2,1), (2,2), (2,3), (3,1), (3,2), (3,3), (4,1), (4,2), (4,3)}

Next, we will find the symmetric difference of (AxB) and (BxA). The symmetric difference of two sets is the set of elements which are in either of the sets, but not in their intersection.

(AxB) ∆ (BxA) = {(1,2), (1,3), (1,4), (2,2), (2,3), (2,4), (3,2), (3,3), (3,4), (2,1), (2,3), (3,1), (3,2), (3,3), (4,1), (4,2), (4,3)} - {(2,2), (2,3), (3,2), (3,3)}

(AxB) ∆ (BxA) = {(1,2), (1,3), (1,4), (2,4), (3,4), (2,1), (3,1), (4,1), (4,2), (4,3)}

Now, let's find the symmetric difference of (BxA) and (AxB).

(BxA) ∆ (AxB) = {(2,1), (2,2), (2,3), (3,1), (3,2), (3,3), (4,1), (4,2), (4,3), (1,2), (1,3), (1,4), (2,2), (2,3), (3,2), (3,3)} - {(2,2), (2,3), (3,2), (3,3)}

(BxA) ∆ (AxB) = {(2,1), (2,4), (3,1), (3,4), (4,1), (4,2), (4,3), (1,2), (1,3), (1,4)}

Notice that (AxB) ∆ (BxA) = {(1,2), (1,3), (1,4), (2,4), (3,4), (2,1), (3,1), (4,1), (4,2), (4,3)} and (BxA) ∆ (AxB) = {(2,1), (2,4), (3,1), (3,4), (4,1), (4,2), (4,3), (1,2), (1,3), (1,4)} are not equal.

Since (AxB) ∆ (BxA) ≠ (BxA) ∆ (AxB), the symmetric difference operation on Cartesian products is not commutative.
